status_message: We had the following interview from Telemundo translated on August 22 2016. https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&q=http://www.telemundo.com/noticias/2016/08/22/alicia-machado-se-hace-ciudadana-de-eeuu-y-envia-un-mensaje-trump?image%3D5204706&source=gmail&ust=1475383999177000&usg=AFQjCNE2NBw9B5L-wOEf5bp-FxIjWx55Ow HOST: What did you feel, Alicia, during that moment? ALICIA MACHADO: Look, I felt very happy, very excited. I've been here many years. I've been to the United States since I was like, I don't know, four or five years old. And also, not only because of these elections which I think are historical for this country; it's historical, too, for the Latino community. The Latino vote is the one that will decide this year many things in these elections. And also, the fact that my daughter is American. My daughter was born here. I have my foundation that is called "Mamis solas" (literally "Moms who are alone", meaning "Single Moms") which I've been working very hard on for five, six years. Also, as an American citizen I can do altruistic work and other types of work legally. And besides, well, our country, Venezuela, which is really in the hands of hatred, and well, my mother is with me, and also by becoming a citizen I have the opportunity to ask for my mom. That way I would have my mom with me. So there are many important reasons HOST: You were, you say, for a long time a resident of the United States... AM: 20 years! How horrible! HOST: And many people, maybe like you, that let a long time go by before becoming American citizens, is there some advice you might have for those people who like you were or are waiting for some reason to take that step for citizenship? AM: Look, I think that by becoming a citizen it enables us to have an opinion, it enables us to complain, it enables us to vote not just for the President, for representatives, for delegates, for all the people that in some way manage this country. And it's a very simple process. I didn't imagine that it would be so easy. And besides, there are many benefits, too. And I think that at this time - I want to use this program to make a call to the Latino community of the United States: this country has given us a lot. The United States is a country that gives us a lot and has given a lot to all of us. The United States has always received, they receive us from so many countries with so many problems. Most of us, it's not my case, but most of us come fleeing the situations of our countries. So I think that at this time the United States - it's the moment for us Latinos to give back to the United States everything they have given us, by voting. HOST: Quickly, many people are afraid of that exam that they give you. Was it hard, was it not hard? AM: No, no! It's not hard. No, it's not hard, and look, you know what? If you don't have a good command of English, don't get stressed out about it because nowadays there are many resources, learning tools, and also I feel that at this time, at immigration level, everything is very smooth precisely because they want us to vote. HOST: Alicia, now that you can vote, what's your message for Donald Trump, quickly? AM: Well look, I'm doing work to support my Latino community. I'm not against anyone. I'm in favor of this country. I'm in favor of freedom, equality. This is a wonderful country with precious foundations at the constitutional level. And that's what I defend. I defend the country of my daughter. And respect for us Hispanics. HOST: But will you send a message to Donald Trump? AM: And I will send him, yes, I sent him a message. And, well yes, now Miss Housekeeping - as he used to call me many times scornfully - now Miss Housekeeping can vote.
link_name: #AliciaMachado: U.S. Making It Easier To Become a Citizen "Because They Want Us To Vote"

status_message:
The WeSearchr investigation was launched to illuminate a long-standing subject of contention and not "an attempted smear" as several pro-McCain POWs contend. 

For decades, POWs and their families have claimed Senator John Sidney McCain III was far from the "war hero" he built his political career upon. The audio recording discovered by our world class team of researchers is the first piece of indisputable evidence in what is quickly becoming a multi-series expose, showing not only clear violation of the military Code of Conduct, but a vindication of the countless Vietnam veterans who were harshly disparaged for sharing their testimony of McCain's propaganda broadcasts. 

This project is being conducted on behalf of all POW's who were killed or tortured; they deserve to have the truth heard. Indeed McCain has worked to seal those records and it's past time that they be revealed for serious journalistic inquiry. This is a transparency exercise first and foremost and continuation of the excellent work the late Pulitzer-Prize winning New York Times columnist Sydney Schanberg. What POW wouldn't want the records released?

It's unfortunate that several POWs have decided to excuse McCain's betrayal and smear my team and me. Neither Jerry Coffee, nor Everett Alvarez, nor Orson Swindle were present for McCain's interrogation by the North Vietnamese. Swindle, for instance, could not have known about McCain's torture because the radio broadcast of McCain's betrayal occurred in 1969 before Swindle became his roommate in 1971-1972. Swindle later worked for an organization alongside Jack Abramoff that lobbied McCain and gave him money. He has an obvious conflict of interest that should have been disclosed in the Arizona Republic article.

"The people responsible for this attempted smear of Johnson's character should be ashamed of themselves," Alvarez, Swindle, and Coffee write shamefully. "They don't deserve the sacrifices he made on their behalf." They further encourage the "American people" to "share our contempt for them." 

I take heroes seriously because my grandfather was a war hero. My grandfather -- Dwight Lyman Johnson -- was a Rear Admiral, Annapolis grad, who earned the Navy Cross for rescuing the flag staff of the U.S.S. Franklin in what was the largest fire to date aboard an aircraft carrier. (The next largest fire aboard an aircraft carrier involved none other than John S. McCain III and the USS Forrestal.) 

The claim that all people broke is disgusting to the POWs who didn't. No one did as many interviews with the enemy as John McCain did. POWs like Olympian Louis Zamperini didn't do enemy broadcasts for Japan despite months of torture. Why did McCain break after only a few days in captivity?  Don't take my work for it. Take McCain's in U.S. News in 1973. "I said, "O.K., I'll give you military information if you will take me to the hospital," McCain wrote. He gave up information right off the bat. Why? McCain's prison guards denied they ever tortured McCain. One even endorsed him for president. Could they be telling the truth? 

John McCain understandably doesn't want to be held responsible for that decision just as he doesn't want the voters to hold him responsible for a whole host of political views he has had over the years. Most notably his decision to meet with and entertain having a sleepover with rebels who later affiliated with ISIS raises questions about his judgment. John McCain hired disgraced neocon analyst Elizabeth O'Bagy long after she was exposed and fired for lying about having a Ph.D. and pushing for American intervention in Syria on behalf of her Syrian rebel paymasters. McCain even cited her discredit reports on the floors of Congress. 

This is just one of the first of WeSearchr's journalistic exploits. There will be many more to come in the future.
